Cloud Cache is an FSLogix feature that provides **high availability and resiliency** for Profile and ODFC containers by maintaining a **local copy of the user profile on the virtual machine** and synchronizing it with one or more **remote storage providers**. It ensures uninterrupted user access during temporary storage or network issues and can support **Business Continuity and Disaster Recovery (BCDR)** across regions, though it increases local **I/O and storage requirements**.

It works by creating a **local cache (VHD file)** during the first sign-in, where user data is stored and accessed. On subsequent sign-ins, the system reuses the existing cache or creates a new one if needed. Data not available locally is fetched from a remote provider (**hydrate**), while all changes are written back to every provider (**flush**). If providers go out of sync, a **clone operation** ensures consistency. Even if remote storage becomes unavailable, the local cache continues to function, though failure to retrieve required data may cause session issues.

Cloud Cache also uses **queue and index files** to track and store changes, a **proxy file** to handle I/O operations, and auxiliary files like the **lock file** (for session ownership) and **meta file** (for tracking the latest data). Storage providers are accessed based on priority, with one used for reading and all used for writing. Overall, Cloud Cache improves reliability, data consistency, and user experience in virtual desktop environments when properly configured.



