Cloud Cache is a feature of FSLogix that works with Profile and ODFC containers to provide **high availability and resiliency** for user profiles. It creates a **local cache of the user’s container on the virtual machine**, which is continuously synchronized with one or more **remote storage providers**. This ensures that users are protected from temporary storage or network issues and can continue working without interruption. It can also be used as part of **Business Continuity and Disaster Recovery (BCDR)** strategies when multiple regions are involved. However, Cloud Cache increases **I/O operations and local storage requirements** on the virtual machine.

Key Considerations of Cloud Cache

* Storage providers are configured using **CCDLocations** and accessed in order of **proximity and preference**.
* Only **one provider is used for reading (hydration)** at a time.
* Data is **written to all configured storage providers** simultaneously.
* Storage performance (latency, bottlenecks) directly affects synchronization.
* Delays in syncing may indicate a **slow or underperforming storage provider**.
* Network tests like ping do not accurately reflect real storage performance.

Cloud Cache Components

1. Local Cache

* A local VHD file is created on the virtual machine (default path: `C:\ProgramData\FSLogix\Cache`).
* During first sign-in:

  * FSLogix creates the container and sets up profile redirection.
  * User profile is loaded into the local cache.
* During subsequent sign-ins:

  * Existing local cache is reused if available.
  * If not, a new cache and proxy file are created.
* Helps maintain user sessions even if remote storage is temporarily unavailable.

2. Cache Objects

Queue Files (*.queue)**: Track pending operations not yet written to storage.
Index Files (*.index)**: Store block-level changes to be written to cache and providers.

3. Remote Storage Providers

* Store **full copies of the user profile container**.
* Used for data access and synchronization across sessions.
* If all providers fail, the **local cache continues functioning** until recovery.
* Failure to read from providers may cause **session hang or system crash (BSOD)**.

key Operations**

hydrate (Read Operation)

* Data is fetched from one remote provider when not available in local cache.
* Happens during sign-in and normal file access.

flush (Write Operation)**

Occurs in three ways:

1. Asynchronous flush**: Data written to all providers simultaneously.
2. During sign-out**: User sign-out may delay until all providers are updated.
3. After failure recovery**: Queued changes are flushed once providers are healthy.

Clone Operation

* Occurs when storage providers are out of sync.
* A full copy of the container is created to ensure consistency across all providers.

Proxy File

* A virtual file representing the user’s container (e.g., `Profile_username.vhd`).
* Handles all I/O operations and buffering.
* Appears large but **does not store actual data**.

Auxiliary Files

Lock File

  * Determines which virtual machine owns the container.
  * Important for **multiple concurrent sessions**.

Meta File

  * Maintains container state and sequence numbers.
  * Helps identify the **most up-to-date storage provider**.


* It relies on external storage systems (e.g., Azure Files, NetApp, etc.) to store profile containers.

